<subSubSection id="C337656CFF87FF91FD97FC43FCA90FF4" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B9236E7FF87FF91FD97FC43FCA90FF4" blockId="34.[151,1436,151,748]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
<emphasis id="B959EAF5FF87FF91FD97FC43FE8F0F99" bold="true" box="[199,328,616,641]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
<emphasis id="B959EAF5FF87FF91FD97FC43FE850F99" bold="true" box="[199,322,616,641]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Comments</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
The striking orange-and-black colour scheme of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2D4D64FF87FF91FE2AFC43FB920F98" authorityName="Luk &amp; Marshall" authorityYear="2014" box="[890,1109,616,640]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Aptilotella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gloriosa">
<emphasis id="B959EAF5FF87FF91FE2AFC43FB920F98" box="[890,1109,616,640]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Aptilotella gloriosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
immediately distinguishes it from its dark brown sympatric relatives, and is matched only by 
<taxonomicName id="4C2D4D64FF87FF91FEF2FCA6FBD50FBC" authorityName="Luk &amp; Marshall" authorityYear="2014" box="[930,1042,652,676]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Aptilotella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sphyra">
<emphasis id="B959EAF5FF87FF91FEF2FCA6FBD50FBC" box="[930,1042,652,676]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">A. sphyra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which has paddle wings and an unmarked frons. This is also the only member of the 
<taxonomicName id="4C2D4D64FF87FF91FFB6FC9BFC940FD0" authorityName="Luk &amp; Marshall" authorityYear="2014" box="[742,851,688,712]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Aptilotella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="corona">
<emphasis id="B959EAF5FF87FF91FFB6FC9BFC940FD0" box="[742,851,688,712]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">A. corona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group in which the tab-like piece is fused to male sternite 5. The very thin bladelike cercus is also distinctive.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
